{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503754"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:06:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:06:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2075"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2075"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.2,0.04,0.68,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79009"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2075"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64358"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3032"},{"type":"tags","id":"3284"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"96"},{"type":"contributions","id":"97"},{"type":"contributions","id":"98"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79009"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of sleep difficulties and fatigue. She has difficulty initiating sleep, taking approximately one hour to fall asleep, and wakes early after only four to five hours of sleep. She reports lying in bed without motivation to start her day. She has experienced decreased appetite and lost interest in her usual hobbies, particularly gardening. These symptoms developed following her husband\u0027s death earlier this year. She lives alone and expresses guilt about being a burden to her family. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears withdrawn with a flat affect. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her BMI is within the healthy range. Cognitive screening tests are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor therapy","Arrange cognitive behavioural therapy","Refer to psychiatrist","Assess suicide risk","Arrange aged care assessment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with major depressive disorder in the context of bereavement, including insomnia, anhedonia, poor appetite, and guilt. Whilst the diagnosis of persistent grief might be considered, the patient\u0027s low mood and lack of interest in and enjoyment of normal activities, point more to a diagnosis of major depressive disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven these symptoms and her risk factors (elderly, recent bereavement, social isolation), \u003Cstrong\u003Eassess suicide risk\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This should include screening for current suicidal thoughts, past attempts, protective factors, and development of a safety plan if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate but should only be initiated after a thorough risk assessment has been completed and documented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange cognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective for mild to moderate depression but should not be arranged until suicide risk has been evaluated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer to psychiatrist\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary depending on the severity of symptoms and level of risk, but is not the most appropriate first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange aged care assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as there is no evidence of functional decline or inability to manage activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDepression in elderly patients requires careful assessment as this population has a higher completed suicide rate compared to other age groups. Recent bereavement, social isolation, and physical health problems are significant risk factors that need to be considered in the assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Risk assessment for suicidal ideation is essential in all patients presenting with symptoms of major depressive disorder.","Elderly patients who have experienced recent bereavement are at particularly high risk of depression and suicide.","Treatment options for depression in elderly patients should only be considered after a comprehensive risk assessment has been performed."],"references":["McCullumsmith C. Laying the Groundwork for Standardized Assessment of Suicidal Behavior. The Journal of Clinical Psychiatry. 2015;76(10):e1333-e1335. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26528662/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64358"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2075"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"item